<typeStatus box="[1802,1886,1407,1447]" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">Type</typeStatus>
locality only.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[1280,2266,993,1815]" box="[1330,1909,1454,1493]" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">Geologic age. Late Tournaisian.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[1280,2266,993,1815]" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">
Etymology. Derived from the Latin 
<taxonomicName box="[1965,2103,1501,1541]" class="Gastropoda" family="Phymatopleuridae" genus="Borestus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurotomariida" pageId="25" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis box="[1965,2103,1501,1541]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning costate, bearing ribs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[1280,2266,993,1815]" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">
Remarks. This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Yoo, 1994" authorityName="Yoo" authorityYear="1994" box="[1985,2263,1593,1632]" class="Gastropoda" family="Soleniscidae" genus="Strobeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="25" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ovalis" status="n.sp.">
<emphasis box="[1985,2263,1593,1632]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">Strobeus ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1280,1365,1639,1678]" pageId="25" pageNumber="88" rank="species">n.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meek &amp; Worthen" authorityYear="1861" box="[1737,1919,1639,1678]" class="Gastropoda" family="Soleniscidae" genus="Soleniscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="[unassigned] Caenogastropoda" pageId="25" pageNumber="88" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1737,1919,1639,1678]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="88">Soleniscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in possessing a columellar fold, but differs in having a thinner shell layer, strongly arched whorls ornamented with fine collabral lirae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
